      <!-- Text Block -->
      <div class="about center">
        <p class="project__description">
          In 2021, I took up the controls lead position and was tasked with
          simply “figuring out how to fly our drone”. With the help of my
          team, I designed from scratch multiple solutions to both vertically
          stabilize and have our drone follow a specific flight path.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Text Block -->
      <div class="about center">
        <p>
          I designed the code base PIPayload, which is written mostly in python,
          handles hardware control, auto pilot, and some simple ground station
          communications. This project, while implemented poorly, displays
          significant research and development into the controls field. I created
          a basic working PID feedback controller, as well as implemented basic
          filtering and fusing. In the area of remote communications, I implemented
          a WIFI ad hoc network to transmit commands and data.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Text Block -->
      <div class="about center">
        <h3>P.L.O.P.</h3>
        <p class="project__description">
          Moving into 2022, We are now creating a Propulsively Landed Microgravity
          Platform, or PLOP. Leaning into what I learned last year, we are going
          above and beyond to ensure a successful launch. This year we are working
          to implement better filtering and fusing algorithms in the form of a
          Kalman filter. We are also moving away from feedback controllers to create
          an LQR or LQG predictive control model. Finally, we are writing all of our
          code in Rust, which will provide us assurance that our control systems won’t
          error out at the most critical times. On top of that, we are implementing my
          VHF Radio PCB to ensure consistent communication at extreme ranges.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Text Block -->
      <div class="about center">
        <p class="project__description">
          The project is still underway however, we have already made significant progress.
          Thus far, we have re-written the majority of our sensor code in Rust and created
          a unique data transmission protocol for sending flight data over VHF while
          maintaining a constant connection. We are currently working on writing a Kalman
          filter and designing a basic PID algorithm for testing purposes, and are on track
          to get the majority of the project done by the start of 2023.
        </p>
      </div>

